# Building a Platform-Compatible Module
 
UCSC Anthropology Portal — developer guide.
 
This document is the checklist for adding a new module so it plugs into the
platform cleanly and never forces edits to other modules. It reflects the
actual contracts in the code as of the platform-services build (EventBus,
Notify, Tasks, the dashboard).
 
The guiding principle behind every rule here: **modules talk to the platform,
never to each other.** A new module should be addable without modifying any
existing module. If you find yourself editing another module to make yours
work, stop — the integration belongs in a platform service instead.
 
---
 
## 1. Anatomy of a module
 
A module is three things:
 
1. **A server handler** — a `.gs` file with an IIFE object of named actions.
2. **A UI partial** — an `.html` file declaring a `window.X` controller.
3. **A registry row** — a row in the **Modules** sheet tab (managed via
   Admin → Modules), NOT code.
 
All three must line up. The module **key** (the registry row's `Key`) is the
permanent dispatch identifier and never changes.
 
---
 
## 2. The server handler (`.gs`)
 
Follow the established pattern (see `Submissionmodule.gs` for a full example):
 
```js
const ThesisModule = (() => {
 
  // Public actions — each is callable via dispatch(module, action, payload).
  // Signature is ALWAYS (payload, user, roles).
  function submit(payload, user, roles) {
    // ... do work via platform services ...
    return { ok: true };
  }
 
  function list(payload, user, roles) { /* ... */ }
 
  return { submit, list };   // only these names are dispatchable
})();
```
 
Rules:
 
- **One IIFE, returning named actions.** Only returned names are reachable
  through `dispatch`.
- **Action signature is `(payload, user, roles)`.** `user` and `roles` are
  injected by `dispatch` from the session — never trust an identity passed in
  the payload.
- **Per-action permission checks** go inside the action. Module-level access
  (who can enter the module at all) is the registry `Roles` list; finer rules
  are per-action. **Always include `super_admin`** in any privileged check.
- **There is no generic `admin` role.** Roles are identity categories
  (`super_admin`, `staff`, `senate_faculty`, `lecturer`, `graduate_student`,
  `undergraduate_student`, `visitor`). Check `roles.includes('super_admin')`,
  never `roles.includes('admin')`. (Some older code checks `'admin'` — do not
  copy that; it is a latent bug.)
- **Read sheet columns by header name, not position** (use DataService, which
  does this for you). Never index a row by a hard-coded column number.
- **Use platform services, never SpreadsheetApp directly** for cross-cutting
  concerns: DataService for data, Notify for email, Tasks for the attention
  queue, Auth for identity, AuditLog (written automatically by dispatch).
 
---
 
## 3. The UI partial (`.html`)
 
```html
<!-- markup uses onclick="ThesisUI.action()" -->
<button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="ThesisUI.submit()">Submit</button>
 
<script>
window.ThesisUI = (() => {          // window.X — NEVER const
  function submit() {
    App.call('thesis', 'submit', payload, onSuccess, onError);
  }
  function init() { /* read window.__focus here — see §6 */ }
  return { submit, init };          // every onclick handler must be exported
})();
ThesisUI.init();
</script>
```
 
Rules:
 
- **Declare the controller as `window.X = (...)`, never `const`.** Module
  scripts are re-executed every time the module loads; `const` would throw
  "already declared" on the second load. This is mandatory.
- **Every `onclick`/`onkeypress` handler must be exported** from the controller
  object, or the markup references an undefined function.
- **Call the server via `App.call(module, action, payload, onSuccess, onError)`**
  — this routes through `dispatch`, which enforces authorization and writes the
  audit log. Do not call `google.script.run` directly for module actions.
- **Reuse shell styles/tokens** (`.card`, `.btn`, `.btn-primary`,
  `--ucsc-navy`, `--color-danger`, etc.) so the module looks native. Add new
  CSS only when necessary.
 
### HTML template scriptlet rules (server-rendered partials)
 
- No bare `<` or `>` inside `<? ?>` scriptlets (use `forEach`, `includes`,
  etc. rather than comparisons that need angle brackets).
- Use `<?!= ?>` (force-print) when injecting JSON into a `<script>` block;
  `<?= ?>` will HTML-escape and break the JSON.
 
---
 
## 4. Registering the module (two code spots + one sheet row)
 
A handler name must appear in **BOTH** of these in `Code.gs`, and ONLY when the
handler's `.gs` file is actually in the project (otherwise "X is not defined"):
 
1. `getModuleHandler()` — maps the handler name string to the code object.
2. `getRegisteredHandlers()` — lists the handler name for the Module Manager.
 
Then add the **Modules sheet row** via Admin → Modules (Key, Label, Icon,
Roles, Handler, Include, Order, Enabled). Deploying code does **not** create the
row — registration is a separate, deliberate step. Keep a module's registration
commented out in `Code.gs` until its `.gs` file ships.
 
---
 
## 5. Using platform services
 
### Tasks — the "needs attention" queue (reporting only)
 
Create a task when work needs a human; resolve it when the underlying record
reaches a terminal state. A task is a **pointer**: it stores routing + a
back-reference, never business data. The module's own sheet is the source of
truth.
 
```js
// Create — assignedTo is a specific user (normal case);
// dueAt / staleAfterDays are optional and DOMAIN-supplied.
const { taskId } = Tasks.create({
  module: 'thesis',
  sourceType: 'thesis_submission',
  sourceId: recordId,                 // id in YOUR module's sheet
  label: 'Thesis awaiting sponsor review',
  assignedTo: sponsorEmail,
  dueAt: new Date('2026-04-15'),      // optional
  staleAfterDays: 14,                 // optional
});
 
// Resolve when your record is done with this step:
Tasks.resolve(taskId, { resolvedBy: user });
// or, without having stored the id:
Tasks.resolveForSource('thesis', recordId, { resolvedBy: user });
```
 
**Tasks reports and escalates visibility; it never owns workflow.** Advancing,
returning, recalling, or reassigning a process is workflow logic and lives in
the module (or a future Workflow layer) — never in Tasks. When the workflow
moves a record, the module calls `Tasks.resolve` on the old task and
`Tasks.create` for the next one.
 
### Notify — email delivery (content stays in your module)
 
Notify resolves recipients, dedupes, formats consistently, and log-and-continues
so a mail failure never breaks your action. It does NOT know what your message
says — you supply the wording.
 
```js
const to = Notify.resolveRecipients({
  superAdmins: CONFIG.SUPER_ADMINS,
  roleRules: NotifyRules.recipientsFor(someRole),
  explicit: [sponsorEmail],
});
Notify.send({ to, subject: 'Thesis submitted', body: '...your wording...' });
```
 
Do not call `Utils.sendEmail` directly for module notifications; route through
Notify so formatting/dedup/logging stay consistent.
 
### EventBus — react to platform events without coupling
 
If your module should react to something another module does, register a
listener in `getEventListeners()` in `Code.gs` (append-only) — never edit the
emitting module. Emit your own events so future modules can react to you:
 
```js
EventBus.emit('thesis.submitted', { recordId, sponsorEmail }, { user });
```
 
A listener that throws is logged/audited and skipped; it can't break the
emitter.
 
### Auth — identity (read, don't duplicate)
 
Get names/IDs/roles via `Auth.getProfile(email)` / `Auth.getRoles(email)`.
Never store your own copy of a person's name or ID. Email is the primary
identity key; IDs are a backup match path (see PersonMatch).
 
### DataService — sheet CRUD by header name
 
`insert`, `update`, `query`, `getAll`, `generateId`. It fills
`CreatedAt/CreatedBy/UpdatedAt/UpdatedBy` automatically when those columns
exist. Always include those meta columns in your tab's headers.
 
---
 
## 6. Deep-linking from the dashboard
 
When a user clicks a task on the dashboard, the shell loads your module and sets
`window.__focus = { sourceType, sourceId, taskId }` **before** your scripts run.
A module that supports deep-linking reads it in `init`:
 
```js
function init() {
  const f = window.__focus;
  if (f && f.sourceId) openRecord(f.sourceId);   // focus that record
}
```
 
Modules that don't implement focus simply ignore `window.__focus`. The shell
never needs to know what you do with it. Fetch the focused record via your own
`App.call` action — the shell does not pre-fetch it.
 
---
 
## 7. Storage tiers (where your data lives)
 
Three tiers (see Config.gs):
 
1. **Config sheet** (`USERS_CONFIG`) — platform identity + registry. Don't put
   module data here.
2. **Platform sheet** (`PLATFORM`) — platform-service operational data (Tasks).
   Not for modules.
3. **Per-module sheet** — your module gets its **own spreadsheet**, referenced
   by a new `CONFIG.SHEETS.<YOURMODULE>` id. A module never holds another
   module's spreadsheet id — that's loose coupling at the data layer.
 
Add your tab(s) to `SETUP_SCHEMA` in `Setup.gs` so `setUp()` creates them.
To add columns to an EXISTING tab later, run `addMissingColumns()` — it appends
missing schema columns non-destructively (never deletes/reorders). `setUp()`
only ever creates missing tabs; it never modifies an existing one.
 
Configuration is UI-managed (Module Manager, Roles, Import permissions, Request
notifications). Avoid telling users to edit sheets directly, except Config.gs
constants.
 
---
 
## 8. Deploy & test
 
- **`/dev`** serves the latest saved code — use it while developing.
- **`/exec`** serves the last **deployed version** — to update it: Deploy →
  Manage deployments → Edit → New version.
- **Syntax-check every `.gs` with `node --check`** before delivery (copy to a
  `.js` extension since Node won't check `.gs` directly).
- **Verify every `onclick` handler is exported** from its UI controller.
- A new top-level `const X` may appear **only once across the whole project**
  (all `.gs` share one global scope) — duplicate declarations throw
  "Identifier 'X' has already been declared."
 
---
 
## 9. Pre-flight checklist for a new module
 
- [ ] Handler `.gs` is an IIFE returning `(payload, user, roles)` actions.
- [ ] Privileged actions check roles and always allow `super_admin`.
- [ ] No use of a generic `admin` role.
- [ ] Columns read by header name (via DataService).
- [ ] UI controller is `window.X`, not `const`; all handlers exported.
- [ ] Server calls go through `App.call` → `dispatch`.
- [ ] Handler registered in BOTH `getModuleHandler()` and
      `getRegisteredHandlers()` — only after the file ships.
- [ ] Modules sheet row added (Admin → Modules).
- [ ] Own spreadsheet + `CONFIG.SHEETS` entry; tab(s) in `SETUP_SCHEMA`.
- [ ] Tasks/Notify/EventBus used for cross-cutting concerns; no direct calls
      into other modules.
- [ ] `window.__focus` read in `init` if the module appears in tasks.
- [ ] All `.gs` pass `node --check`; project loads with no duplicate-const error.
